I believe the ad refers to the American Paralympic swimmer Jessica Long. The ad essentially is about someone taking the risk to do something not entirely popular, let alone something minimally feasible, for the simple reason that the one taking the risk believes that something good will come of it, solely by dint of the fact that that person possess hope and strength, and that that person believes that that hope and strength can, will, and therefore ought be carried over into the expected good outcome warranted by the initial strong hopeful taking of the risk.

Apparently, so does Toyota - "Proud Partner of Team USA".

IMHO:
The risk in question is adoption from a foreign country - specifically, from Russia, and particularly from Siberia.
The good that comes out of it is the adoption of the child into the family - specifically, the adoption of the young Russian girl from Siberia into the adoptive family.
The person possessing hope and strength is the prospective adopted mother who, out of the apparent sole desire to gift her love to her prospective adopted daughter, chooses to adopt this girl against all apparent conceivable doubt that anything good will come out of it.
The good outcome warranted by the strength and hope in the prospective adoptive mother is effected largely by the gifting of this strength and hope from her to her adopted daughter [without the transfer thereof, obviously], which good outcome is manifestly obviously apparent in the Toyota commercial.

The commercial checks out: it's a true story. A simple Google search of the name of the swimmer in question will verify this.

We should be consistent and EITHER respect all companies who might want to spend their advertising dollars putting out a message they believe in OR consistently reject ideological ads, even when we agree with them.

I'm in favor of free speech, and letting companies express their values. (See all the crazy Thai life insurance commercials that drives everyone to tears because they have more emotional content than most full-length movies in America).

The EV commercial is cute and pointless at the same time.

Nearly all (97%) of Norway's electrical production comes from established hydro-electric installation and renewables. The USA uses about 65% fossil fuel to generate the electricity for "green" things like EVs.

The critical point in the ad is that Norway is beating the US in EVs measured PER CAPITA.

Norway has a population of about 5.5 million (similar to Colorado but with 100,000 sq kms more land area). Of that, about 4.1 million are of legal driving age (+16) and may have drivers licenses. About 230 million Americans have drivers licenses.

There are only 465,000 EVs in Norway compared to 1.4 million in the USA. And there are still about 2.4 million petroleum passenger cars in the country. There are 264 million cars in the US.

The World Bank ranks Norway as the richest country in the world per capita from an economy based on petroleum and natural resources. https://www.newsinenglish.no/2018/02/05/norway-is-now-the-richest-in-the-world/
Oil production is through the state owned company Statoil and is not part of OPEC. Profit flows directly to the government.

And those mountains in the background of the ad (albeit Sweden) hold huge additional hydro potential as needed.

Electrifying Norway is logical, simple and affordable compared to the US and many other places.

As shown in the ad, comparing Norway's energy situation with the USA is best presented by a comedian. Cute ad.

Disclaimer to eco-pozers: That ad is not a documentary and is meant for entertainment purposes only. Facts don't care about your green feelings. Now eat your soup.

The rule: Do or say something controversial that piggybacks on a current social debate or narrative and people will talk about it for weeks, with the hope that they will remember the brand!  This works.  It doesn't necessarily  need to make sense.  It just needs to disrupt the current narrative and keep people talking.  I am not so sure this commercial achieved that goal. i am a farmer and the jeep ad was just weird, i want to know why the horse was loose while saddled up, you dont leave your horse unattended out of a pasture. i mean his costume was pretty accurate, it was just way to clean, and his hands were to soft, so he can't pass as a farmer to anyone who knows what a farmer looks like, my hands are super rough, and my fingernails always have dirt under them, my hands are also brown a lot of the time from how dirty they are, my knuckles are black when i come in from a day of work. my clothes are also always covered in dirt and animal hair, they are never clean like his, my clothes pretty much all have mud stains on them. it isn't an easy life, and i'm sick of companies making it look easy, or trying to appeal to us by having some city slicker pretend to be country. the discipline, humility, and work ethic needed are intense, we rely on nature to keep us afloat, Bruce Springsteen will never know how much work the country people, who are mostly conservatives, put in to get him food on the table. i'm sure he eats good food since he has the money, but that came from someone's hard work. he doesn't know what it's like to sit up all night with a sick and cold baby animal to have it die in your arms, he hasn't gone out to feed his goats to find the baby one had in the middle of the night frozen solid, sorry if that is disturbing to some of you but that's life, he doesn't understand what that is like, despite the common misconception we aren't heartless. we don't feel nothing when an animal dies, the reason we're able to raise meat animals is because we go into it knowing what they are. we go into it knowing that they will die. it still hurts, it is still weird to feed an animal, to care for it for weeks, or months, and then it's gone. and the animals that aren't meat animals we love fiercely, milk cows, goats, horses, dogs, we love those animals with a fire ignited by god our creator. when we loose a goat, or a horse, or a dog, our family is devastated, we move on but it hurts, my younger brother is the most sensitive when it come to this kind of thing, i mean it happens, we know that but it still hurts. my horses are my best friends, the work i put into them to get them to where they are is my greatest achievement. i love my goats and i hate when i find one of them injured, we have lost animals and yeah it sucks, but we move on, something a lot of democrats can't do over anything. it is sickening to see rich people who haven't worked as hard as i work every day in their entire lives trying to take advantage of us, the lady gaga Biden ad did the same thing, it was offensive, and i'm not offended by much, but the way she talked, and acted she was clearly appealing to rural voters and talking like we are stupid. i spend my day's fighting with animals, and making food for my family, we make most of our own food, but the way people disrespect the people putting food on their tables. i saw one quote that sums it up perfectly, i don't remember who said it but it was this, "the farmer skips dinner so you don't have to." we work hard sunrise till sundown everyday to put food on the table of the ungrateful people who don't understand. i have been pulled over fences by goats, i have been knocked to the ground my goats and mini cows running into the back of my legs, i have been kicked, bitten, stepped on, bucked off, thrown to the ground, and so much more by 1,200 LBS animals, machines made of muscle and solid bone. i have fallen 6 ft traveling at 30 MPH, i wouldn't trade this life for anything, but people who know nothing about it don't get to talk down to me. people in the cities work hard yes, but i do physical labor all day everyday, i work outside in 10 degree temperatures to keep my animals safe and healthy, i brave the wind, rain, and much more weather issues to protect them, we go outside in the middle of the night, risking the threat of mountain lions, wolves, and coyotes to save a baby animal from the frigid temperatures. i know this as really long winded but i just needed to say something from the perspective of a farmer, we are underappreciated and that's fine, but don't disrespect us, we are tough as nails and will take you out. people rely on us, don't disrespect the people who create the food you need to live
